results.name: Spiko US T-Bills Money Market Fund
results.description: Spiko US T-Bills Money Market Fund is a short-term variable net asset value money market fund (short-term VNAV MMF) under EU law and a sub-fund of the Spiko SICAV. The Fund invests 100% of its total assets in U.S. Treasury Bills (T-Bills), repurchase agreements secured by such securities and cash.The Fund keeps an average maturity of its portfolio under 60 days. The maximum maturity of any asset held by the Fund is less than 6 months. The cash holdings cannot exceed 10% of its total assets.
results.transparency_description: The Fund is broadcasting its net asset value and total assets under management on each business to all major financial data providers (Bloomberg, Morningstar, etc.) as well as to its supervisory authority. The Fund is publishing its portfolio on spiko.xyz daily. The Fund is also publishing an annual report.
results.holder_rights_description: Shareholders in the Fund are entitled to redeem their shareholding and receive the redemption proceeds relating to such shares as detailed in the Fund’s prospectus.
results.legal_structure__description: French SICAV (Société dinvestissement à capital variable)
results.regulatory_framework: UCITS Directive (Directive 2009/65/CE) & MMF Regulation (Regulation (EU) 2017/1131)
results.governing_body: AMF - French Autorité des Marchés Financiers
results.primary_market__redemption_description: To redeem their shares, investors make an on-chain transfer to a redemption smart contract. The Spiko platform UI abstracts this on-chain transfer for investors who want to. Redemption orders must be received prior to the daily cutoff time (10:30 AM CET each business day) in order to be executed on the same day. Redemption orders received after the daily cutoff time are executed on the next business day.
results.accounts_segregated_description: The UCITS Directive requires segregation of assets to protect investors and ensure fund assets can be identified at any time. Financial instruments must be registered in segregated accounts in the name of the UCITS. UCITS assets must be separated from the assets of the depositary.
results.holdings_bankruptcy_remote_description: UCITS assets must be separated from the assets of the depositary and the depositary must ensure that assets held by sub-custodians are not available to pay off creditors in case of the sub-custodian's insolvency.
